# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: low-pass-filter
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:low-pass-filter/acoustics] Hearing is one of the most crucial means of survival in the animal world and speech is one of the most distinctive characteristics of human development and culture.
[src:low-pass-filter/acoustics] Accordingly, the science of acoustics spreads across many facets of human society—music, medicine, architecture, industrial production, warfare and more.
[src:low-pass-filter/acoustics] Likewise, animal species such as songbirds and frogs use sound and hearing as a key element of mating rituals or for marking territories.
[src:low-pass-filter/acoustics] Art, craft, science and technology have provoked one another to advance the whole, as in many other fields of knowledge.
[src:low-pass-filter/acoustics] Robert Bruce Lindsay's "Wheel of Acoustics" is a well-accepted overview of the various fields in acoustics.
[src:low-pass-filter/acoustics] The word "acoustic" is derived from the ἀκουστικός (*akoustikós*), meaning "of or for hearing" and "ready to hear", and from ἀκουστός (*akoustós*), "heard, audible", which in turn derives from the verb ἀκούω (*akoúō*), "to hear".
[src:low-pass-filter/acoustics] The Latin synonym is "sonic", after which the term **sonics** used to be a synonym for acoustics and later a branch of acoustics.
[src:low-pass-filter/acoustics] Frequencies above and below the audible range are called "ultrasonic" and "infrasonic", respectively.
[src:low-pass-filter/acoustics] In the 6th century BCE, the ancient Greek philosopher Pythagoras wanted to know why some combinations of musical sounds seemed more beautiful than others, and he found answers in terms of numerical ratios representing the harmonic overtone series on a string.
[src:low-pass-filter/acoustics] He is reputed to have observed that when the lengths of vibrating strings are expressible as ratios of integers (e.g.
[src:low-pass-filter/acoustics] 2 to 3, 3 to 4), the tones produced will be harmonious, and the smaller the integers the more harmonious the sounds.
[src:low-pass-filter/acoustics] For example, a string of a certain length would sound particularly harmonious with a string of twice the length (other factors being equal).
[src:low-pass-filter/acoustics] In modern parlance, if a string sounds the note C when plucked, a string twice as long will sound a C an octave lower.
[src:low-pass-filter/acoustics] In one system of musical tuning, the tones in between are then given by 16:9 for D, 8:5 for E, 3:2 for F, 4:3 for G, 6:5 for A, and 16:15 for B, in ascending order.
[src:low-pass-filter/acoustics] Aristotle (384–322 BCE) understood that sound consisted of compressions and rarefactions of air which "falls upon and strikes the air which is next to it...", a very good expression of the nature of wave motion.
[src:low-pass-filter/acoustics] *On Things Heard*, generally ascribed to Strato of Lampsacus, states that the pitch is related to the frequency of vibrations of the air and to the speed of sound.
[src:low-pass-filter/acoustics] In about 20 BCE, the Roman architect and engineer Vitruvius wrote a treatise on the acoustic properties of theaters, including a discussion of interference, echoes, and reverberation—the beginnings of architectural acoustics.
[src:low-pass-filter/acoustics] In Book V of his *De architectura* (*The Ten Books of Architecture*) Vitruvius described sound as a wave comparable to a water wave extended to three dimensions, which, when interrupted by obstructions, would flow back and break up following waves.
[src:low-pass-filter/acoustics] During the Islamic golden age, Abū Rayhān al-Bīrūnī (973–1048) is believed to have postulated that the speed of sound was much slower than the speed of light.
[src:low-pass-filter/acoustics] The physical understanding of acoustical processes advanced rapidly during and after the Scientific Revolution.
[src:low-pass-filter/acoustics] Mainly Galileo Galilei (1564–1642) but also Marin Mersenne (1588–1648), independently, discovered the complete laws of vibrating strings (completing what Pythagoras and Pythagoreans had started 2000 years earlier).
[src:low-pass-filter/acoustics] Galileo wrote "Waves are produced by the vibrations of a sonorous body, which spread through the air, bringing to the tympanum of the ear a stimulus which the mind interprets as sound", a remarkable statement that points to the beginnings of physiological and psychological acoustics.
[src:low-pass-filter/acoustics] Experimental measurements of the speed of sound in air were carried out successfully between 1630 and 1680 by a number of investigators, prominently Mersenne.
[src:low-pass-filter/acoustics] Inspired by Mersenne's *Harmonie universelle* (*Universal Harmony*) of 1634, the Rome-based Jesuit scholar Athanasius Kircher undertook research in acoustics.
[src:low-pass-filter/acoustics] Kircher published two major books on acoustics: the *Musurgia universalis* (*Universal Music-Making*) in 1650 and the *Phonurgia nova* (*New Sound-Making*) in 1673.
[src:low-pass-filter/acoustics] Meanwhile, Newton (1642–1727) derived the relationship for wave velocity in solids, a cornerstone of physical acoustics (Principia, 1687).
[src:low-pass-filter/acoustics] Substantial progress in acoustics, resting on firmer mathematical and physical concepts, was made during the eighteenth century by Euler (1707–1783), Lagrange (1736–1813), and d'Alembert (1717–1783).
[src:low-pass-filter/acoustics] During this era, continuum physics, or field theory, began to receive a definite mathematical structure.
[src:low-pass-filter/acoustics] The wave equation emerged in a number of contexts, including the propagation of sound in air.
[src:low-pass-filter/acoustics] Also in the 19th century, Wheatstone, Ohm, and Henry developed the analogy between electricity and acoustics.
[src:low-pass-filter/acoustics] The twentieth century saw a burgeoning of technological applications of the large body of scientific knowledge that was by then in place.
[src:low-pass-filter/acoustics] The first such application was Sabine's groundbreaking work in architectural acoustics, and many others followed.
[src:low-pass-filter/acoustics] Underwater acoustics was used for detecting submarines in the First World War.
[src:low-pass-filter/acoustics] Sound recording and the telephone played important roles in a global transformation of society.
[src:low-pass-filter/acoustics] Sound measurement and analysis reached new levels of accuracy and sophistication through the use of electronics and computing.
[src:low-pass-filter/acoustics] The ultrasonic frequency range enabled wholly new kinds of application in medicine and industry.
[src:low-pass-filter/acoustics] New kinds of transducers (generators and receivers of acoustic energy) were invented and put to use.
[src:low-pass-filter/acoustics] , both suspended on an overhead steel trellis, to synthesize an indoor acoustic environment outdoors.
[src:low-pass-filter/acoustics] Acoustics is defined by ANSI/ASA S1.1-2013 as "(a) Science of sound, including its production, transmission, and effects, including biological and psychological effects.
[src:low-pass-filter/acoustics] The study of acoustics revolves around the generation, propagation and reception of mechanical waves and vibrations.
[src:low-pass-filter/acoustics] The steps shown in the above diagram can be found in any acoustical event or process.
[src:low-pass-filter/acoustics] There are many kinds of causes, both natural and volitional.
[src:low-pass-filter/acoustics] There are many kinds of transduction processes that convert energy from some other form into sonic energy, producing a sound wave.
[src:low-pass-filter/acoustics] There is one fundamental equation that describes sound wave propagation, the acoustic wave equation, but the phenomena that emerge from it are varied and often complex.
[src:low-pass-filter/acoustics] The wave carries energy throughout the propagating medium.
[src:low-pass-filter/acoustics] Eventually this energy is transduced again into other forms, in ways that again may be natural and/or volitionally contrived.
[src:low-pass-filter/acoustics] The final effect may be purely physical or it may reach far into the biological or volitional domains.
[src:low-pass-filter/acoustics] The five basic steps are found equally well whether we are talking about an earthquake, a submarine using sonar to locate its foe, or a band playing in a rock concert.
[src:low-pass-filter/acoustics] The central stage in the acoustical process is wave propagation.
[src:low-pass-filter/acoustics] This falls within the domain of physical acoustics.
[src:low-pass-filter/acoustics] In fluids, sound propagates primarily as a pressure wave.
[src:low-pass-filter/acoustics] In solids, mechanical waves can take many forms including longitudinal waves, transverse waves and surface waves.
[src:low-pass-filter/acoustics] Acoustics looks first at the pressure levels and frequencies in the sound wave and how the wave interacts with the environment.
[src:low-pass-filter/acoustics] This interaction can be described as either a diffraction, interference or a reflection or a mix of the three.
[src:low-pass-filter/acoustics] If several media are present, a refraction can also occur.
[src:low-pass-filter/acoustics] Transduction processes are also of special importance to acoustics.
[src:low-pass-filter/acoustics] In fluids such as air and water, sound waves propagate as disturbances in the ambient pressure level.
[src:low-pass-filter/acoustics] While this disturbance is usually small, it is still noticeable to the human ear.
[src:low-pass-filter/acoustics] The smallest sound that a person can hear, known as the threshold of hearing, is nine orders of magnitude smaller than the ambient pressure.
[src:low-pass-filter/acoustics] The loudness of these disturbances is related to the sound pressure level (SPL), which is measured on a logarithmic scale in decibels.
[src:low-pass-filter/acoustics] Physicists and acoustic engineers tend to discuss sound pressure levels in terms of frequencies, partly because this is how our ears interpret sound.
[src:low-pass-filter/acoustics] What we experience as "higher pitched" or "lower pitched" sounds are pressure vibrations having a higher or lower number of cycles per second.
[src:low-pass-filter/acoustics] In a common technique of acoustic measurement, acoustic signals are sampled in time, and then presented in more meaningful forms such as octave bands or time frequency plots.
[src:low-pass-filter/acoustics] Both of these popular methods are used to analyze sound and better understand the acoustic phenomenon.
[src:low-pass-filter/acoustics] The entire spectrum can be divided into three sections: audio, ultrasonic, and infrasonic.
[src:low-pass-filter/acoustics] The audio range falls between 20 Hz and 20,000 Hz.
[src:low-pass-filter/acoustics] This range is important because its frequencies can be detected by the human ear.
[src:low-pass-filter/acoustics] This range has a number of applications, including speech communication and music.
[src:low-pass-filter/acoustics] The ultrasonic range refers to the very high frequencies: 20,000 Hz and higher.
[src:low-pass-filter/acoustics] This range has shorter wavelengths which allow better resolution in imaging technologies.
[src:low-pass-filter/acoustics] Medical applications such as ultrasonography and elastography rely on the ultrasonic frequency range.
[src:low-pass-filter/acoustics] On the other end of the spectrum, the lowest frequencies are known as the infrasonic range.
[src:low-pass-filter/acoustics] These frequencies can be used to study geological phenomena such as earthquakes.
[src:low-pass-filter/acoustics] Analytic instruments such as the spectrum analyzer facilitate visualization and measurement of acoustic signals and their properties.
[src:low-pass-filter/acoustics] The spectrogram produced by such an instrument is a graphical display of the time varying pressure level and frequency profiles that give a specific acoustic signal its defining character.
[src:low-pass-filter/acoustics] A transducer is a device for converting one form of energy into another.
[src:low-pass-filter/acoustics] In an electroacoustic context, this means converting sound energy into electrical energy (or vice versa).
[src:low-pass-filter/acoustics] Electroacoustic transducers include loudspeakers, microphones, particle velocity sensors, hydrophones and sonar projectors.
[src:low-pass-filter/acoustics] These devices convert a sound wave to or from an electric signal.
[src:low-pass-filter/acoustics] The most widely used transduction principles are electromagnetism, electrostatics and piezoelectricity.
[src:low-pass-filter/acoustics] The transducers in most common loudspeakers (e.g. woofers and tweeters), are electromagnetic devices that generate waves using a suspended diaphragm driven by an electromagnetic voice coil, sending off pressure waves.
[src:low-pass-filter/acoustics] Electret microphones and condenser microphones employ electrostatics—as the sound wave strikes the microphone's diaphragm, it moves and induces a voltage change.
[src:low-pass-filter/acoustics] The ultrasonic systems used in medical ultrasonography employ piezoelectric transducers.
[src:low-pass-filter/acoustics] These are made from special ceramics in which mechanical vibrations and electrical fields are interlinked through a property of the material itself.
[src:low-pass-filter/acoustics] An acoustician is an expert in the science of sound.
[src:low-pass-filter/acoustics] There are many types of acousticians, but they usually have a Bachelor's degree or higher qualification.
[src:low-pass-filter/acoustics] Some possess a degree in acoustics, while others enter the discipline via studies in fields such as physics or engineering.
[src:low-pass-filter/acoustics] Much work in acoustics requires a good grounding in mathematics and science.
[src:low-pass-filter/acoustics] Many acoustic scientists work in research and development.
[src:low-pass-filter/acoustics] Some conduct basic research to advance our knowledge of the perception (e.g. hearing, psychoacoustics or neurophysiology) of speech, music and noise.
[src:low-pass-filter/acoustics] Other acoustic scientists advance understanding of how sound is affected as it moves through environments, e.g. underwater acoustics, architectural acoustics or structural acoustics.
[src:low-pass-filter/acoustics] Other areas of work are listed under subdisciplines below.
[src:low-pass-filter/acoustics] Acoustic scientists work in government, university and private industry laboratories.
[src:low-pass-filter/acoustics] Many go on to work in acoustical engineering.
[src:low-pass-filter/acoustics] Some positions, such as faculty (academic staff) require a Doctor of Philosophy.
[src:low-pass-filter/acoustics] Archaeoacoustics, also known as the archaeology of sound, is one of the only ways to experience the past with senses other than our eyes.
[src:low-pass-filter/acoustics] Archaeoacoustics is studied by testing the acoustic properties of prehistoric sites, including caves.
[src:low-pass-filter/acoustics] Iegor Rezkinoff, a sound archaeologist, studies the acoustic properties of caves through natural sounds like humming and whistling.
[src:low-pass-filter/acoustics] Archaeological theories of acoustics are focused around ritualistic purposes as well as a way of echolocation in the caves.
[src:low-pass-filter/acoustics] In archaeology, acoustic sounds and rituals directly correlate as specific sounds were meant to bring ritual participants closer to a spiritual awakening.
[src:low-pass-filter/acoustics] Parallels can also be drawn between cave wall paintings and the acoustic properties of the cave; they are both dynamic.
[src:low-pass-filter/acoustics] Because archaeoacoustics is a fairly new archaeological subject, acoustic sound is still being tested in these prehistoric sites today.
[src:low-pass-filter/acoustics] Aeroacoustics is the study of noise generated by air movement, for instance via turbulence, and the movement of sound through the fluid air.
[src:low-pass-filter/acoustics] This knowledge was applied in the 1920s and '30s to detect aircraft before radar was invented and is applied in acoustical engineering to study how to quieten aircraft.
[src:low-pass-filter/acoustics] Aeroacoustics is important for understanding how wind musical instruments work.
[src:low-pass-filter/acoustics] Acoustic signal processing is the electronic manipulation of acoustic signals.
[src:low-pass-filter/acoustics] Applications include: active noise control; design for hearing aids or cochlear implants; echo cancellation; music information retrieval, and perceptual coding (e.g.
[src:low-pass-filter/acoustics] Architectural acoustics (also known as building acoustics) involves the scientific understanding of how to achieve good sound within a building.
[src:low-pass-filter/acoustics] It typically involves the study of speech intelligibility, speech privacy, music quality, and vibration reduction in the built environment.
[src:low-pass-filter/acoustics] Commonly studied environments are hospitals, classrooms, dwellings, performance venues, recording and broadcasting studios.
[src:low-pass-filter/acoustics] Focus considerations include room acoustics, airborne and impact transmission in building structures, airborne and structure-borne noise control, noise control of building systems and electroacoustic systems.
[src:low-pass-filter/acoustics] Bioacoustics is the scientific study of the hearing and calls of animals, as well as how animals are affected by the acoustic and sounds of their habitat.
[src:low-pass-filter/acoustics] This subdiscipline is concerned with the recording, manipulation and reproduction of audio using electronics.
[src:low-pass-filter/acoustics] This might include products such as mobile phones, large scale public address systems or virtual reality systems in research laboratories.
[src:low-pass-filter/acoustics] Environmental acoustics is the study of noise and vibrations, and their impact on structures, objects, humans, and animals.
[src:low-pass-filter/acoustics] The main aim of these studies is to reduce levels of environmental noise and vibration.
[src:low-pass-filter/acoustics] Typical work and research within environmental acoustics concerns the development of models used in simulations, measurement techniques, noise mitigation strategies, and the development of standards and regulations.
[src:low-pass-filter/acoustics] Research work now also has a focus on the positive use of sound in urban environments: soundscapes and tranquility.
[src:low-pass-filter/acoustics] Examples of noise and vibration sources include railways, road traffic, aircraft, industrial equipment and recreational activities.
[src:low-pass-filter/acoustics] Musical acoustics is the study of the physics of acoustic instruments; the audio signal processing used in electronic music; the computer analysis of music and composition, and the perception and cognitive neuroscience of music.
[src:low-pass-filter/acoustics] Many studies have been conducted to identify the relationship between acoustics and cognition, or more commonly known as psychoacoustics, in which what one hears is a combination of perception and biological aspects.
[src:low-pass-filter/acoustics] The information intercepted by the passage of sound waves through the ear is understood and interpreted through the brain, emphasizing the connection between the mind and acoustics.
[src:low-pass-filter/acoustics] Psychological changes have been seen as brain waves slow down or speed up as a result of varying auditory stimulus which can in turn affect the way one thinks, feels, or even behaves.
[src:low-pass-filter/acoustics] This correlation can be viewed in normal, everyday situations in which listening to an upbeat or uptempo song can cause one's foot to start tapping or a slower song can leave one feeling calm and serene.
[src:low-pass-filter/acoustics] In a deeper biological look at the phenomenon of psychoacoustics, it was discovered that the central nervous system is activated by basic acoustical characteristics of music.
[src:low-pass-filter/acoustics] By observing how the central nervous system, which includes the brain and spine, is influenced by acoustics, the pathway in which acoustics affects the mind, and essentially the body, is evident.
[src:low-pass-filter/acoustics] Acousticians study the production, processing and perception of speech.
[src:low-pass-filter/acoustics] Speech recognition and speech synthesis are two important areas of speech processing using computers.
[src:low-pass-filter/acoustics] The subject also overlaps with the disciplines of physics, physiology, psychology, and linguistics.
[src:low-pass-filter/acoustics] Structural acoustics is the study of motions and interactions of mechanical systems with their environments and the methods of their measurement, analysis, and control.
[src:low-pass-filter/acoustics] Ultrasonics deals with sounds at frequencies too high to be heard by humans.
[src:low-pass-filter/acoustics] Specialisms include medical ultrasonics (including medical ultrasonography), ultrasonic sensors, sonochemistry, ultrasonic testing, material characterisation and underwater acoustics (sonar).
[src:low-pass-filter/acoustics] Underwater acoustics is the scientific study of natural and man-made sounds underwater.
[src:low-pass-filter/acoustics] Applications include sonar to locate submarines, underwater communication by whales, climate change monitoring by measuring sea temperatures acoustically, sonic weapons, and marine bioacoustics.
[src:low-pass-filter/active-device] An **electronic component** is any basic discrete electronic device or physical entity part of an electronic system used to affect electrons or their associated fields.
[src:low-pass-filter/active-device] Electronic components are mostly industrial products, available in a singular form and are not to be confused with electrical elements, which are conceptual abstractions representing idealized electronic components and elements.
[src:low-pass-filter/active-device] A datasheet for an electronic component is a technical document that provides detailed information about the component's specifications, characteristics, and performance.
[src:low-pass-filter/active-device] Discrete circuits are made of individual electronic components that only perform one function each as packaged, which are known as discrete components, although strictly the term discrete component refers to such a component with semiconductor material such as individual transistors.
[src:low-pass-filter/active-device] Electronic components have a number of electrical terminals or leads.
[src:low-pass-filter/active-device] These leads connect to other electrical components, often over wire, to create an electronic circuit with a particular function (for example an amplifier, radio receiver, or oscillator).
[src:low-pass-filter/active-device] Basic electronic components may be packaged discretely, as arrays or networks of like components, or integrated inside of packages such as semiconductor integrated circuits, hybrid integrated circuits, or thick film devices.
[src:low-pass-filter/active-device] The following list of electronic components focuses on the discrete version of these components, treating such packages as components in their own right.
[src:low-pass-filter/active-device] Components can be classified as passive, active, or electromechanical.
[src:low-pass-filter/active-device] The strict physics definition treats passive components as ones that cannot supply energy themselves, whereas a battery would be seen as an active component since it truly acts as a source of energy.
[src:low-pass-filter/active-device] However, electronic engineers who perform circuit analysis use a more restrictive definition of passivity.
[src:low-pass-filter/active-device] Then, the analysis only concerns the AC circuit, an abstraction that ignores DC voltages and currents (and the power associated with them) present in the real-life circuit.
[src:low-pass-filter/active-device] This fiction, for instance, lets us view an oscillator as "producing energy" even though in reality the oscillator consumes even more energy from a DC power supply, which we have chosen to ignore.
[src:low-pass-filter/active-device] Most passive components with more than two terminals can be described in terms of two-port parameters that satisfy the principle of reciprocity—though there are rare exceptions.
[src:low-pass-filter/active-device] In contrast, active components (with more than two terminals) generally lack that property.
[src:low-pass-filter/active-device] Transistors were considered the invention of the twentieth century that changed electronic circuits forever.
[src:low-pass-filter/active-device] A transistor is a semiconductor device used to amplify and switch electronic signals and electrical power.
[src:low-pass-filter/active-device] Conduct electricity easily in one direction, among more specific behaviors.
[src:low-pass-filter/active-device] Integrated Circuits can serve a variety of purposes, including acting as a timer, performing digital to analog conversion, performing amplification, or being used for logical operations.
[src:low-pass-filter/active-device] A vacuum tube is based on current conduction through a vacuum (see Vacuum tube).
[src:low-pass-filter/active-device] Components incapable of controlling current by means of another electrical signal are called *passive* devices.
[src:low-pass-filter/active-device] Resistors, capacitors, inductors, and transformers are all considered passive devices.
[src:low-pass-filter/active-device] Pass current in proportion to voltage (Ohm's law) and oppose current.
[src:low-pass-filter/active-device] Capacitors store and release electrical charge.
[src:low-pass-filter/active-device] They are used for filtering power supply lines, tuning resonant circuits, and for blocking DC voltages while passing AC signals, among numerous other uses.
[src:low-pass-filter/active-device] Integrated passive devices are passive devices integrated within one distinct package.
[src:low-pass-filter/active-device] They take up less space than equivalent combinations of discrete components.
[src:low-pass-filter/active-device] Electrical components that pass charge in proportion to magnetism or magnetic flux, and have the ability to retain a previous resistive state, hence the name of Memory plus Resistor.
[src:low-pass-filter/active-device] Sensors (detectors) are transducers that react to environmental conditions by changing their electrical properties or generating an electrical signal.
[src:low-pass-filter/active-device] The transducers listed here are single electronic components (as opposed to complete assemblies), and are passive (see Semiconductors and Tubes for active ones).
[src:low-pass-filter/active-device] Only the most common ones are listed here.
[src:low-pass-filter/active-device] On a circuit diagram, electronic devices are represented by conventional symbols.
[src:low-pass-filter/active-device] Reference designators are applied to the symbols to identify the components.
[src:low-pass-filter/active-filter] An **active filter** is a type of analog circuit implementing an electronic filter using active components, typically an amplifier.
[src:low-pass-filter/active-filter] Amplifiers included in a filter design can be used to improve the cost, performance and predictability of a filter.
[src:low-pass-filter/active-filter] An amplifier prevents the load impedance of the following stage from affecting the characteristics of the filter.
[src:low-pass-filter/active-filter] An active filter can have complex poles and zeros without using a bulky or expensive inductor.
[src:low-pass-filter/active-filter] The shape of the response, the Q (quality factor), and the tuned frequency can often be set with inexpensive variable resistors.
[src:low-pass-filter/active-filter] In some active filter circuits, one parameter can be adjusted without affecting the others.
[src:low-pass-filter/active-filter] Using active elements has some limitations.
[src:low-pass-filter/active-filter] Basic filter design equations neglect the finite bandwidth of amplifiers.
[src:low-pass-filter/active-filter] Available active devices have limited bandwidth, so they are often impractical at high frequencies.
[src:low-pass-filter/active-filter] Amplifiers consume power and inject noise into a system.
[src:low-pass-filter/active-filter] Certain circuit topologies may be impractical if no DC path is provided for bias current to the amplifier elements.
[src:low-pass-filter/active-filter] Power handling capability is limited by the amplifier stages.
[src:low-pass-filter/active-filter] Active filters can implement the same transfer functions as passive filters.
[src:low-pass-filter/active-filter] where most of the offending rumble comes from a particular frequency).
[src:low-pass-filter/active-filter] An active filter can have gain, increasing the power available in a signal compared to the input.
[src:low-pass-filter/active-filter] Passive filters dissipate energy from a signal and cannot have a net power gain.
[src:low-pass-filter/active-filter] This advantage may not be as important for active filters entirely integrated on a chip because the available capacitors have relatively low values and so require high value resistors which take up area of the integrated circuit.
[src:low-pass-filter/active-filter] Active filters have good isolation between stages, and can provide high input impedance and low output impedance; this makes their characteristics independent of the source and load impedances.
[src:low-pass-filter/active-filter] Multiple stages can be cascaded when desired to improve characteristics.
[src:low-pass-filter/active-filter] In contrast, design of multiple-stage passive filters must take into account each stage's frequency-dependent loading of the preceding stage.
[src:low-pass-filter/active-filter] It is feasible to make active filters tunable over a wide range, compared with passive filters.
[src:low-pass-filter/active-filter] Since inductors are not used, filters can be made in a very compact size and do not produce or interact with magnetic fields that may be present.
[src:low-pass-filter/active-filter] Compared with active filters, passive filters require no additional power supplies.
[src:low-pass-filter/active-filter] The amplifying devices of an active filter must provide predictable gain and performance over the entire frequency range to be processed; the gain–bandwidth product of the amplifier will constrain the maximum frequency that can be used.
[src:low-pass-filter/adel-sedra] Sedra received his B.Sc. from Cairo University in 1964 and his M.A.Sc. and Ph.D. from the University of Toronto, in 1968 and 1969, respectively.
[src:low-pass-filter/adel-sedra] All three of his degrees are in electrical engineering.
[src:low-pass-filter/adel-sedra] Sedra joined the faculty of the University of Toronto in 1969 and became associate professor in 1972 and professor in 1978.
[src:low-pass-filter/adel-sedra] He served as chair of the Department of Electrical Engineering from 1986 to 1993, and was vice president, provost, and chief academic officer from July 1, 1993, to 2002.
[src:low-pass-filter/adel-sedra] In his nine years as provost Sedra led the university through two major long-range planning cycles in 1994 and 1998.
[src:low-pass-filter/adel-sedra] On July 1, 2003, Sedra joined the University of Waterloo as dean of its Faculty of Engineering and as professor of electrical and computer engineering.
[src:low-pass-filter/adel-sedra] In 2004 he initiated the University of Waterloo Engineering Planning Exercise, VISION 2010.
[src:low-pass-filter/adel-sedra] He served as Dean of Engineering until June 2012.
[src:low-pass-filter/adel-sedra] A specialist in microelectronics, Sedra's research focuses on applications in communication and instrumentation systems, including theory and design of circuits.
[src:low-pass-filter/adel-sedra] Sedra has co-authored three textbooks, including *Microelectronic Circuits* (with co-author K.C.
[src:low-pass-filter/adel-sedra] Smith), now in its eighth edition (2019).
[src:low-pass-filter/adel-sedra] The text is published in ten languages, has over one million copies in print, and is one of the most widely used texts on the subject to date.
[src:low-pass-filter/adel-sedra] Roberts of the text book *SPICE for Microelectronic Circuits* published in 1995.
[src:low-pass-filter/adel-sedra] His first text book (with co-author Peter O.
[src:low-pass-filter/adel-sedra] Brackett) titled *Filter Theory and Design: Active and Passive* was published in 1978.
[src:low-pass-filter/adel-sedra] Sedra has published about 150 scholarly papers, has guided the research of about 65 graduate students, and has also served as a consultant to industry and governments in Canada and the United States.
[src:low-pass-filter/adel-sedra] From 1990 to 1994, Sedra was a member of the Scientific Assessment Panel for the Industry Research Program of Technology Ontario, and is currently a member of the Research Council of the Canadian Institute for Advanced Research.
[src:low-pass-filter/adel-sedra] Sedra served as a delegate to Oxford University Press (1995–2008) and is currently editing the Oxford Electrical and Computer Engineering Series.
[src:low-pass-filter/adel-sedra] More recently, Sedra chaired a committee that reviewed the Structure of NSERC Grant Selection Committees.
[src:low-pass-filter/adel-sedra] Sedra was elected fellow of the Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers (1984), the Canadian Academy of Engineering (1999), and the Royal Society of Canada (2003).
[src:low-pass-filter/adel-sedra] Sedra Distinguished Graduate Award" was created by the University of Toronto Alumni Association (UTAA), to honor Sedra for his accomplishments during his nine years as vice-president and provost of the University of Toronto.
[src:low-pass-filter/adel-sedra] For every year since 2003, it has been awarded "to a graduate student who demonstrates outstanding academic and extracurricular leadership".
[src:low-pass-filter/adel-sedra] In 2013, the University of Waterloo's 20,000-square-foot student design centre located in Engineering 5 was named the "Sedra Student Design Centre" to honour Sedra as a former Dean of Waterloo Engineering.
[src:low-pass-filter/adel-sedra] In 2014, he was made a Member of the Order of Ontario in recognition for his " seminal work which has resulted in major developments in fields ranging from medical technology to wireless communications".
[src:low-pass-filter/all-pass-filter] An **all-pass filter** is a signal processing filter that passes all frequencies equally in gain, but changes the phase relationship among various frequencies.
[src:low-pass-filter/all-pass-filter] Most types of filter reduce the amplitude (i.e. the magnitude) of the signal applied to it for some values of frequency, whereas the all-pass filter allows all frequencies through without changes in level.
[src:low-pass-filter/all-pass-filter] A common application in electronic music production is in the design of an effects unit known as a "phaser", where a number of all-pass filters are connected in sequence and the output mixed with the raw signal.
[src:low-pass-filter/all-pass-filter] It does this by varying its phase shift as a function of frequency.
[src:low-pass-filter/all-pass-filter] Generally, the filter is described by the frequency at which the phase shift crosses 90° (i.e., when the input and output signals go into quadrature – when there is a quarter wavelength of delay between them).
[src:low-pass-filter/all-pass-filter] They are generally used to compensate for other undesired phase shifts that arise in the system, or for mixing with an unshifted version of the original to implement a notch comb filter.
[src:low-pass-filter/all-pass-filter] They may also be used to convert a mixed phase filter into a minimum phase filter with an equivalent magnitude response or an unstable filter into a stable filter with an equivalent magnitude response.
[src:low-pass-filter/all-pass-filter] The operational amplifier circuit shown in adjacent figure implements a single-pole active all-pass filter that features a low-pass filter at the non-inverting input of the opamp.
[src:low-pass-filter/all-pass-filter] which has one pole at -1/RC and one zero at 1/RC (i.e., they are *reflections* of each other across the imaginary axis of the complex plane).
[src:low-pass-filter/all-pass-filter] The filter has unity-gain magnitude for all ω.
[src:low-pass-filter/all-pass-filter] The filter introduces a different delay at each frequency and reaches input-to-output *quadrature* at ω=1/RC (i.e., phase shift is 90°).
[src:low-pass-filter/all-pass-filter] This implementation uses a low-pass filter at the non-inverting input to generate the phase shift and negative feedback.
[src:low-pass-filter/all-pass-filter] In fact, the phase shift of the all-pass filter is double the phase shift of the low-pass filter at its non-inverting input.
[src:low-pass-filter/all-pass-filter] where T is the delay (in seconds) and $s\in \mathbb {C}$ is complex frequency.
[src:low-pass-filter/all-pass-filter] where the last step was achieved via a first-order Taylor series expansion of the numerator and denominator.
[src:low-pass-filter/all-pass-filter] By setting $RC=T/2$ we recover $H(s)$ from above.
[src:low-pass-filter/all-pass-filter] The operational amplifier circuit shown in the adjacent figure implements a single-pole active all-pass filter that features a high-pass filter at the non-inverting input of the opamp.
[src:low-pass-filter/all-pass-filter] The filter introduces a different delay at each frequency and reaches input-to-output *quadrature* at ω=1/RC (i.e., phase lead is 90°).
[src:low-pass-filter/all-pass-filter] This implementation uses a high-pass filter at the non-inverting input to generate the phase shift and negative feedback.
[src:low-pass-filter/all-pass-filter] In fact, the phase shift of the all-pass filter is double the phase shift of the high-pass filter at its non-inverting input.
[src:low-pass-filter/all-pass-filter] The resistor can be replaced with a FET in its *ohmic mode* to implement a voltage-controlled phase shifter; the voltage on the gate adjusts the phase shift.
[src:low-pass-filter/all-pass-filter] In electronic music, a phaser typically consists of two, four or six of these phase-shifting sections connected in tandem and summed with the original.
[src:low-pass-filter/all-pass-filter] A low-frequency oscillator (LFO) ramps the control voltage to produce the characteristic swooshing sound.
[src:low-pass-filter/all-pass-filter] The benefit to implementing all-pass filters with active components like operational amplifiers is that they do not require inductors, which are bulky and costly in integrated circuit designs.
[src:low-pass-filter/all-pass-filter] In other applications where inductors are readily available, all-pass filters can be implemented entirely without active components.
[src:low-pass-filter/all-pass-filter] There are a number of circuit topologies that can be used for this.
[src:low-pass-filter/all-pass-filter] The following are the most commonly used circuits.
[src:low-pass-filter/all-pass-filter] The **lattice phase equaliser**, or **filter**, is a filter composed of lattice, or X-sections.
[src:low-pass-filter/all-pass-filter] With single element branches it can produce a phase shift up to 180°, and with resonant branches it can produce phase shifts up to 360°.
[src:low-pass-filter/all-pass-filter] The filter is an example of a constant-resistance network (i.e., its image impedance is constant over all frequencies).
[src:low-pass-filter/all-pass-filter] The phase equaliser based on T topology is the unbalanced equivalent of the lattice filter and has the same phase response.
[src:low-pass-filter/all-pass-filter] While the circuit diagram may look like a low pass filter it is different in that the two inductor branches are mutually coupled.
[src:low-pass-filter/all-pass-filter] This results in transformer action between the two inductors and an all-pass response even at high frequency.
[src:low-pass-filter/all-pass-filter] The bridged T topology is used for delay equalisation, particularly the differential delay between two landlines being used for stereophonic sound broadcasts.
[src:low-pass-filter/all-pass-filter] This application requires that the filter has a linear phase response with frequency (i.e., constant group delay) over a wide bandwidth and is the reason for choosing this topology.
[src:low-pass-filter/all-pass-filter] which has a zero at $1/{\overline {z_{0}}}$ , where ${\overline {z}}$ denotes the complex conjugate.
[src:low-pass-filter/all-pass-filter] The pole and zero sit at the same angle but have reciprocal magnitudes (i.e., they are *reflections* of each other across the boundary of the complex unit circle).
[src:low-pass-filter/all-pass-filter] The placement of this pole-zero pair for a given $z_{0}$ can be rotated in the complex plane by any angle and retain its all-pass magnitude characteristic.
[src:low-pass-filter/all-pass-filter] Complex pole-zero pairs in all-pass filters help control the frequency where phase shifts occur.
[src:low-pass-filter/all-pass-filter] where $y[k]$ is the output and $x[k]$ is the input at discrete time step k .
[src:low-pass-filter/all-pass-filter] Filters such as the above can be cascaded with unstable or mixed-phase filters to create a stable or minimum-phase filter without changing the magnitude response of the system.
[src:low-pass-filter/all-pass-filter] For example, by proper choice of $z_{0}$ , a pole of an unstable system that is outside of the unit circle can be canceled and reflected inside the unit circle.
[src:low-pass-filter/alternating-current] The usual waveform of alternating current in most electric power circuits is a sine wave, whose positive half-period corresponds with positive direction of the current and vice versa (the full period is called a *cycle*).
[src:low-pass-filter/alternating-current] "Alternating current" most commonly refers to power distribution, but a wide range of other applications are technically alternating current although it is less common to describe them by that term.
[src:low-pass-filter/alternating-current] In many applications, like guitar amplifiers, different waveforms are used, such as triangular waves or square waves.
[src:low-pass-filter/alternating-current] Audio and radio signals carried on electrical wires are also examples of alternating current.
[src:low-pass-filter/alternating-current] These types of alternating current carry information such as sound (audio) or images (video) sometimes carried by modulation of an AC carrier signal.
[src:low-pass-filter/alternating-current] These currents typically alternate at higher frequencies than those used in power transmission.
[src:low-pass-filter/alternating-current] Electrical energy is distributed as alternating current because AC voltage may be increased or decreased with a transformer.
[src:low-pass-filter/alternating-current] This allows the power to be transmitted through power lines efficiently at high voltage, which reduces the energy lost as heat due to resistance of the wire, and transformed to a lower, safer voltage for use.
[src:low-pass-filter/alternating-current] Use of a higher voltage leads to significantly more efficient transmission of power.
[src:low-pass-filter/alternating-current] This means that when transmitting a fixed power on a given wire, if the current is halved (by doubling the voltage), the power loss due to the wire's resistance will be reduced by a factor of four.
[src:low-pass-filter/alternating-current] Consequently, power transmitted at a higher voltage requires less loss-producing current than for the same power at a lower voltage.
[src:low-pass-filter/alternating-current] Power is often transmitted at hundreds of kilovolts on pylons, and transformed down to tens of kilovolts to be transmitted on lower level lines, and finally transformed down to 100 V – 240 V for domestic use.
[src:low-pass-filter/alternating-current] High voltages have disadvantages, such as the increased insulation required, and generally increased difficulty in their safe handling.
[src:low-pass-filter/alternating-current] In a power plant, energy is generated at a convenient voltage for the design of a generator, and then stepped up to a high voltage for transmission.
[src:low-pass-filter/alternating-current] Near the loads, the transmission voltage is stepped down to the voltages used by equipment.
[src:low-pass-filter/alternating-current] Consumer voltages vary somewhat depending on the country and size of load, but generally motors and lighting are built to use up to a few hundred volts between phases.
[src:low-pass-filter/alternating-current] The voltage delivered to equipment such as lighting and motor loads is standardized, with an allowable range of voltage over which equipment is expected to operate.
[src:low-pass-filter/alternating-current] Standard power utilization voltages and percentage tolerance vary in the different mains power systems found in the world.
[src:low-pass-filter/alternating-current] High-voltage direct-current (HVDC) electric power transmission systems have become more viable as technology has provided efficient means of changing the voltage of DC power.
[src:low-pass-filter/alternating-current] Transmission with high voltage direct current was not feasible in the early days of electric power transmission, as there was then no economically viable way to step the voltage of DC down for end user applications such as lighting incandescent bulbs.
[src:low-pass-filter/alternating-current] Three-phase electrical generation is very common.
[src:low-pass-filter/alternating-current] The simplest way is to use three separate coils in the generator stator, physically offset by an angle of 120° (one-third of a complete 360° phase) to each other.
[src:low-pass-filter/alternating-current] Three current waveforms are produced that are equal in magnitude and 120° out of phase to each other.
[src:low-pass-filter/alternating-current] If coils are added opposite to these (60° spacing), they generate the same phases with reverse polarity and can be wired together.
[src:low-pass-filter/alternating-current] In practice, higher *pole orders* are commonly used.
[src:low-pass-filter/alternating-current] For example, a 12-pole machine would have 36 coils (10° spacing).
[src:low-pass-filter/alternating-current] The advantage is that lower rotational speeds can be used to generate the same frequency.
[src:low-pass-filter/alternating-current] For example, a 2-pole machine running at 3600 rpm and a 12-pole machine running at 600 rpm produce the same frequency; the lower speed is preferable for larger machines.
[src:low-pass-filter/alternating-current] If the load on a three-phase system is balanced equally among the phases, no current flows through the neutral point.
[src:low-pass-filter/alternating-current] Even in the worst-case unbalanced (linear) load, the neutral current will not exceed the highest of the phase currents.
[src:low-pass-filter/alternating-current] Non-linear loads (e.g. the switch-mode power supplies widely used) may require an oversized neutral bus and neutral conductor in the upstream distribution panel to handle harmonics.
[src:low-pass-filter/alternating-current] Harmonics can cause neutral conductor current levels to exceed that of one or all phase conductors.
[src:low-pass-filter/alternating-current] For three-phase at utilization voltages a four-wire system is often used.
[src:low-pass-filter/alternating-current] When stepping down three-phase, a transformer with a Delta (3-wire) primary and a Star (4-wire, center-earthed) secondary is often used so there is no need for a neutral on the supply side.
[src:low-pass-filter/alternating-current] For smaller customers (just how small varies by country and age of the installation) only a single phase and neutral, or two phases and neutral, are taken to the property.
[src:low-pass-filter/alternating-current] For larger installations, all three phases and neutral are taken to the main distribution panel.
[src:low-pass-filter/alternating-current] From the three-phase main panel, both single and three-phase circuits may lead off.
[src:low-pass-filter/alternating-current] Three-wire single-phase systems, with a single center-tapped transformer giving two live conductors, is a common distribution scheme for residential and small commercial buildings in North America.
[src:low-pass-filter/alternating-current] This arrangement is sometimes incorrectly referred to as *two phase*.
[src:low-pass-filter/alternating-current] A similar method is used for a different reason on construction sites in the UK.
[src:low-pass-filter/alternating-current] Small power tools and lighting are supposed to be supplied by a local center-tapped transformer with a voltage of 55 V between each power conductor and earth.
[src:low-pass-filter/alternating-current] This significantly reduces the risk of electric shock in the event that one of the live conductors becomes exposed through an equipment fault whilst still allowing a reasonable voltage of 110 V between the two conductors for running the tools.
[src:low-pass-filter/alternating-current] An additional wire, called the bond (or earth) wire, is often connected between non-current-carrying metal enclosures and earth ground.
[src:low-pass-filter/alternating-current] This conductor provides protection from electric shock due to accidental contact of circuit conductors with the metal chassis of portable appliances and tools.
[src:low-pass-filter/alternating-current] Bonding all non-current-carrying metal parts into one complete system ensures there is always a low electrical impedance path to ground sufficient to carry any fault current for as long as it takes for the system to clear the fault.
[src:low-pass-filter/alternating-current] This low impedance path allows the maximum amount of fault current, causing the overcurrent protection device (breakers, fuses) to trip or burn out as quickly as possible, bringing the electrical system to a safe state.
[src:low-pass-filter/alternating-current] All bond wires are bonded to ground at the main service panel, as is the neutral/identified conductor if present.
[src:low-pass-filter/alternating-current] The frequency of the electrical system varies by country and sometimes within a country; most electric power is generated at either 50 or 60 Hz.
[src:low-pass-filter/alternating-current] Some countries have a mixture of 50 Hz and 60 Hz supplies, notably electricity power transmission in Japan.
[src:low-pass-filter/alternating-current] A low frequency eases the design of electric motors, particularly for hoisting, crushing and rolling applications, and commutator-type traction motors for applications such as railways.
[src:low-pass-filter/alternating-current] However, low frequency also causes noticeable flicker in arc lamps and incandescent light bulbs.
[src:low-pass-filter/alternating-current] The use of lower frequencies also provided the advantage of lower transmission losses, which are proportional to frequency.
[src:low-pass-filter/alternating-current] The original Niagara Falls generators were built to produce 25 Hz power, as a compromise between low frequency for traction and heavy induction motors, while still allowing incandescent lighting to operate (although with noticeable flicker).
[src:low-pass-filter/alternating-current] Most of the 25 Hz residential and commercial customers for Niagara Falls power were converted to 60 Hz by the late 1950s, although some 25 Hz industrial customers still existed as of the start of the 21st century.
[src:low-pass-filter/alternating-current] 16.7 Hz power (formerly 16 2/3 Hz) is still used in some European rail systems, such as in Austria, Germany, Norway, Sweden and Switzerland.
[src:low-pass-filter/alternating-current] Off-shore, military, textile industry, marine, aircraft, and spacecraft applications sometimes use 400 Hz, for benefits of reduced weight of apparatus or higher motor speeds.
[src:low-pass-filter/alternating-current] Computer mainframe systems were often powered by 400 Hz or 415 Hz for benefits of ripple reduction while using smaller internal AC to DC conversion units.
[src:low-pass-filter/alternating-current] A direct current flows uniformly throughout the cross-section of a homogeneous electrically conducting wire.
[src:low-pass-filter/alternating-current] An alternating current of any frequency is forced away from the wire's center, toward its outer surface.
[src:low-pass-filter/alternating-current] This is because an alternating current (which is the result of the acceleration of electric charge) creates electromagnetic waves (a phenomenon known as electromagnetic radiation).
[src:low-pass-filter/alternating-current] The phenomenon of alternating current being pushed away from the center of the conductor is called skin effect, and a direct current does not exhibit this effect, since a direct current does not create electromagnetic waves.
[src:low-pass-filter/alternating-current] At very high frequencies, the current no longer flows *in* the wire, but effectively flows *on* the surface of the wire, within a thickness of a few skin depths.
[src:low-pass-filter/alternating-current] The skin depth is the thickness at which the current density is reduced by 63%.
[src:low-pass-filter/alternating-current] Even at relatively low frequencies used for power transmission (50 Hz – 60 Hz), non-uniform distribution of current still occurs in sufficiently thick conductors.
[src:low-pass-filter/alternating-current] For example, the skin depth of a copper conductor is approximately 8.57 mm at 60 Hz, so high-current conductors are usually hollow to reduce their mass and cost.
[src:low-pass-filter/alternating-current] This tendency of alternating current to flow predominantly in the periphery of conductors reduces the effective cross-section of the conductor.
[src:low-pass-filter/alternating-current] This increases the effective AC resistance of the conductor since resistance is inversely proportional to the cross-sectional area.
[src:low-pass-filter/alternating-current] A conductor's AC resistance is higher than its DC resistance, causing a higher energy loss due to Ohmic heating (also called I2R loss).
[src:low-pass-filter/alternating-current] For low to medium frequencies, conductors can be divided into stranded wires, each insulated from the others, with the relative positions of individual strands specially arranged within the conductor bundle.
[src:low-pass-filter/alternating-current] Wire constructed using this technique is called Litz wire.
[src:low-pass-filter/alternating-current] This measure helps to partially mitigate skin effect by forcing more equal current throughout the total cross section of the stranded conductors.
[src:low-pass-filter/alternating-current] As written above, an alternating current is made of electric charge under periodic acceleration, which causes radiation of electromagnetic waves.
[src:low-pass-filter/alternating-current] Depending on the frequency, different techniques are used to minimize the loss due to radiation.
[src:low-pass-filter/alternating-current] At frequencies up to about 1 GHz, pairs of wires are twisted together in a cable, forming a twisted pair.
[src:low-pass-filter/alternating-current] This reduces losses from electromagnetic radiation and inductive coupling.
[src:low-pass-filter/alternating-current] A twisted pair must be used with a balanced signaling system so that the two wires carry equal but opposite currents.
[src:low-pass-filter/alternating-current] Each wire in a twisted pair radiates a signal, but it is effectively canceled by radiation from the other wire, resulting in almost no radiation loss.
[src:low-pass-filter/alternating-current] Coaxial cables are commonly used at audio frequencies and above for convenience.
[src:low-pass-filter/alternating-current] A coaxial cable has a conductive wire inside a conductive tube, separated by a dielectric layer.
[src:low-pass-filter/alternating-current] The current flowing on the surface of the inner conductor is equal and opposite to the current flowing on the inner surface of the outer tube.
[src:low-pass-filter/alternating-current] The electromagnetic field is thus completely contained within the tube, and (ideally) no energy is lost to radiation or coupling outside the tube.
[src:low-pass-filter/alternating-current] Coaxial cables have acceptably small losses for frequencies up to about 5 GHz.
[src:low-pass-filter/alternating-current] For microwave frequencies greater than 5 GHz, the losses (due mainly to the dielectric separating the inner and outer tubes being a non-ideal insulator) become too large, making waveguides a more efficient medium for transmitting energy.
[src:low-pass-filter/alternating-current] Coaxial cables often use a perforated dielectric layer to separate the inner and outer conductors in order to minimize the power dissipated by the dielectric.
[src:low-pass-filter/alternating-current] Waveguides are similar to coaxial cables, as both consist of tubes, with the biggest difference being that waveguides have no inner conductor.
[src:low-pass-filter/alternating-current] Waveguides can have any arbitrary cross section, but rectangular cross sections are the most common.
[src:low-pass-filter/alternating-current] Because waveguides do not have an inner conductor to carry a return current, waveguides cannot deliver energy by means of an electric current, but rather by means of a *guided* electromagnetic field.
[src:low-pass-filter/alternating-current] Although surface currents do flow on the inner walls of the waveguides, those surface currents do not carry power.
[src:low-pass-filter/alternating-current] Power is carried by the guided electromagnetic fields.
[src:low-pass-filter/alternating-current] The surface currents are set up by the guided electromagnetic fields and have the effect of keeping the fields inside the waveguide and preventing leakage of the fields to the space outside the waveguide.
[src:low-pass-filter/alternating-current] Waveguides have dimensions comparable to the wavelength of the alternating current to be transmitted, so they are feasible only at microwave frequencies.
[src:low-pass-filter/alternating-current] In addition to this mechanical feasibility, electrical resistance of the non-ideal metals forming the walls of the waveguide causes dissipation of power (surface currents flowing on lossy conductors dissipate power).
[src:low-pass-filter/alternating-current] At higher frequencies, the power lost to this dissipation becomes unacceptably large.
[src:low-pass-filter/alternating-current] At frequencies greater than 200 GHz, waveguide dimensions become impractically small, and the ohmic losses in the waveguide walls become large.
[src:low-pass-filter/alternating-current] Instead, fiber optics, which are a form of dielectric waveguides, can be used.
[src:low-pass-filter/alternating-current] For such frequencies, the concepts of voltages and currents are no longer used.
[src:low-pass-filter/alternating-current] Alternating currents are accompanied (or caused) by alternating voltages.
[src:low-pass-filter/alternating-current] The peak-to-peak value of an AC voltage is defined as the difference between its positive peak and its negative peak.
[src:low-pass-filter/alternating-current] Since the maximum value of $\sin(x)$ is +1 and the minimum value is −1, an AC voltage swings between $+V_{\text{peak}}$ and $-V_{\text{peak}}$ .
[src:low-pass-filter/alternating-current] Below an AC waveform (with no DC component) is assumed.
[src:low-pass-filter/alternating-current] The RMS voltage is the square root of the mean over one cycle of the square of the instantaneous voltage.
[src:low-pass-filter/alternating-current] Rather than using instantaneous power, $p(t)$ , it is more practical to use a time-averaged power (where the averaging is performed over any integer number of cycles).
[src:low-pass-filter/alternating-current] For this reason, AC power's waveform becomes Full-wave rectified sine, and its fundamental frequency is double that of the voltage's.
[src:low-pass-filter/alternating-current] To illustrate these concepts, consider a 230 V AC mains supply used in many countries around the world.
[src:low-pass-filter/alternating-current] It is so called because its root mean square value is 230 V.
[src:low-pass-filter/alternating-current] This means that the time-averaged power delivered $P_{\text{average}}$ is equivalent to the power delivered by a DC voltage of 230 V.
[src:low-pass-filter/alternating-current] For 230 V AC, the peak voltage $V_{\text{peak}}$ is therefore $230{\text{ V}}\times {\sqrt {2}}$ , which is about 325 V, and the peak power $P_{\text{peak}}$ is $230\times R\times W\times 2$ , that is 460 RW.
[src:low-pass-filter/alternating-current] During the course of one cycle (two cycle as the power) the voltage rises from zero to 325 V, the power from zero to 460 RW, and both falls through zero.
[src:low-pass-filter/alternating-current] Next, the voltage descends to reverse direction, −325 V, but the power ascends again to 460 RW, and both returns to zero.
[src:low-pass-filter/alternating-current] Alternating current is used to transmit information, as in the cases of telephone and cable television.
[src:low-pass-filter/alternating-current] Information signals are carried over a wide range of AC frequencies.
[src:low-pass-filter/alternating-current] POTS telephone signals have a frequency of about 3 kHz, close to the baseband audio frequency.
[src:low-pass-filter/alternating-current] Cable television and other cable-transmitted information currents may alternate at frequencies of tens to thousands of megahertz.
[src:low-pass-filter/alternating-current] These frequencies are similar to the electromagnetic wave frequencies often used to transmit the same types of information over the air.
[src:low-pass-filter/alternating-current] The first alternator to produce alternating current was an electric generator based on Michael Faraday's principles constructed by the French instrument maker Hippolyte Pixii in 1832.
[src:low-pass-filter/alternating-current] Pixii later added a commutator to his device to produce the (then) more commonly used direct current.
[src:low-pass-filter/alternating-current] The earliest recorded practical application of alternating current is by Guillaume Duchenne, inventor and developer of electrotherapy.
[src:low-pass-filter/alternating-current] In 1855, he announced that AC was superior to direct current for electrotherapeutic triggering of muscle contractions.
[src:low-pass-filter/alternating-current] Alternating current technology was developed further by the Hungarian Ganz Works company in the 1870s, and, in the 1880s, by Sebastian Ziani de Ferranti, Lucien Gaulard, and Galileo Ferraris.
[src:low-pass-filter/alternating-current] In 1876, Russian engineer Pavel Yablochkov invented a lighting system where sets of induction coils were installed along a high-voltage AC line.
[src:low-pass-filter/alternating-current] Instead of changing voltage, the primary windings transferred power to the secondary windings which were connected to one or several electric candles (arc lamps) of his own design, used to keep the failure of one lamp from disabling the entire circuit.
[src:low-pass-filter/alternating-current] In 1878, the Ganz factory, Budapest, Hungary, began manufacturing equipment for electric lighting and, by 1883, had installed over fifty systems in Austria-Hungary.
[src:low-pass-filter/alternating-current] Their AC systems used arc and incandescent lamps, generators, and other equipment.
[src:low-pass-filter/alternating-current] The development of the alternating current transformer to change voltage from low to high level and back, allowed generation and consumption at low voltages and transmission, over great distances, at high voltage, with savings in the cost of conductors and energy losses.
[src:low-pass-filter/alternating-current] A bipolar open-core power transformer developed by Lucien Gaulard and John Dixon Gibbs was demonstrated in London in 1881, and attracted the interest of Westinghouse.
[src:low-pass-filter/alternating-current] They exhibited an AC system powering arc and incandescent lights was installed along five railway stations for the Metropolitan Railway in London and a single-phase multiple-user AC distribution system Turin in 1884.
[src:low-pass-filter/alternating-current] These early induction coils with open magnetic circuits were inefficient at transferring power to loads.
[src:low-pass-filter/alternating-current] Until about 1880, the paradigm for AC power transmission from a high voltage supply to a low voltage load was a series circuit.
[src:low-pass-filter/alternating-current] Open-core transformers with a ratio near 1:1 were connected with their primaries in series to allow use of a high voltage for transmission while presenting a low voltage to the lamps.
[src:low-pass-filter/alternating-current] The inherent flaw in this method was that turning off a single lamp (or other electronic device) affected the voltage supplied to all others on the same circuit.
[src:low-pass-filter/alternating-current] Many adjustable transformer designs were introduced to compensate for this problematic characteristic of the series circuit, including those employing methods of adjusting the core or bypassing the magnetic flux around part of a coil.
[src:low-pass-filter/alternating-current] The direct current systems did not have these drawbacks, giving it significant advantages over early AC systems.
[src:low-pass-filter/alternating-current] In 1890, he designed their power station at Deptford and converted the Grosvenor Gallery station across the Thames into an electrical substation, showing the way to integrate older plants into a universal AC supply system.
[src:low-pass-filter/alternating-current] In the autumn of 1884, Károly Zipernowsky, Ottó Bláthy and Miksa Déri (ZBD), three engineers associated with the Ganz Works of Budapest, determined that open-core devices were impractical, as they were incapable of reliably regulating voltage.
[src:low-pass-filter/alternating-current] In both designs, the magnetic flux linking the primary and secondary windings traveled almost entirely within the confines of the iron core, with no intentional path through air (see toroidal cores).
[src:low-pass-filter/alternating-current] The new transformers were 3.4 times more efficient than the open-core bipolar devices of Gaulard and Gibbs.
[src:low-pass-filter/alternating-current] The Ganz factory in 1884 shipped the world's first five high-efficiency AC transformers.
[src:low-pass-filter/alternating-current] This first unit had been manufactured to the following specifications: 1,400 W, 40 Hz, 120:72 V, 11.6:19.4 A, ratio 1.67:1, one-phase, shell form.
[src:low-pass-filter/alternating-current] When employed in parallel connected electric distribution systems, closed-core transformers finally made it technically and economically feasible to provide electric power for lighting in homes, businesses and public spaces.
[src:low-pass-filter/alternating-current] The other essential milestone was the introduction of 'voltage source, voltage intensive' (VSVI) systems' by the invention of constant voltage generators in 1885.
[src:low-pass-filter/alternating-current] In early 1885, the three engineers also eliminated the problem of eddy current losses with the invention of the lamination of electromagnetic cores.
[src:low-pass-filter/alternating-current] Ottó Bláthy also invented the first AC electricity meter.
[src:low-pass-filter/alternating-current] In May 1885, at the Hungarian National Exhibition in Budapest, Deri, Blathy, and Zipernowski held a large-scale demonstration of what is widely regarded as the prototype of modern AC lighting systems.
[src:low-pass-filter/alternating-current] Their system used 75 transformers in parallel connection, supplying 1,067 incandescent Edison lamps from an AC generator that provided 1,350 V.
[src:low-pass-filter/alternating-current] The AC power system was developed and adopted rapidly after 1886.
[src:low-pass-filter/alternating-current] With this setup, the Westinghouse company successfully powered thirty 100-volt incandescent bulbs in twenty shops along the main street of Great Barrington.
[src:low-pass-filter/alternating-current] By the fall of that year Ganz engineers installed a ZBD transformer power system with AC generators in Rome.
[src:low-pass-filter/alternating-current] Based on Stanley's success, the new Westinghouse Electric went on to develop alternating current (AC) electric infrastructure throughout the United States.
[src:low-pass-filter/alternating-current] The spread of Westinghouse and other AC systems triggered a push back in late 1887 by Thomas Edison (a proponent of direct current), who attempted to discredit alternating current as too dangerous in a public campaign called the "war of the currents".
[src:low-pass-filter/alternating-current] In 1888, alternating current systems gained further viability with the introduction of a functional AC motor, something these systems had lacked up till then.
[src:low-pass-filter/alternating-current] The design, an induction motor, was independently invented by Galileo Ferraris and Nikola Tesla (with Tesla's design being licensed by Westinghouse in the US).
[src:low-pass-filter/alternating-current] This design was independently further developed into the modern practical three-phase form by Mikhail Dolivo-Dobrovolsky and Charles Eugene Lancelot Brown in Germany on one side, and Jonas Wenström in Sweden on the other, though Brown favored the two-phase system.
[src:low-pass-filter/alternating-current] The Ames Hydroelectric Generating Plant, constructed in 1890, was among the first hydroelectric alternating current power plants.
[src:low-pass-filter/alternating-current] A long-distance transmission of single-phase electricity from a hydroelectric generating plant in Oregon at Willamette Falls sent power fourteen miles downriver to downtown Portland for street lighting in 1890.
[src:low-pass-filter/alternating-current] In 1891, another transmission system was installed in Telluride Colorado.
[src:low-pass-filter/alternating-current] The first three-phase system was established in 1891 in Frankfurt, Germany.
[src:low-pass-filter/alternating-current] The Tivoli–Rome transmission was completed in 1892.
[src:low-pass-filter/alternating-current] The San Antonio Canyon Generator was the third commercial single-phase hydroelectric AC power plant in the United States to provide long-distance electricity.
[src:low-pass-filter/alternating-current] It was completed on December 31, 1892, by Almarian William Decker to provide power to the city of Pomona, California, which was 14 miles away.
[src:low-pass-filter/alternating-current] Meanwhile, the possibility of transferring electrical power from a waterfall at a distance was explored at the Grängesberg mine in Sweden.
[src:low-pass-filter/alternating-current] A 45 m fall at Hällsjön, Smedjebackens kommun, where a small iron work had been located, was selected.
[src:low-pass-filter/alternating-current] In 1893, a three-phase 9.5 kv system was used to transfer 400 horsepower a distance of 15 km, becoming the first commercial application.
[src:low-pass-filter/alternating-current] In 1893, Westinghouse built an alternating current system for the Chicago World Exposition.
[src:low-pass-filter/alternating-current] In 1893, Decker designed the first American commercial three-phase power plant using alternating current—the hydroelectric Mill Creek No.
[src:low-pass-filter/alternating-current] 1 Hydroelectric Plant near Redlands, California.
[src:low-pass-filter/alternating-current] Decker's design incorporated 10 kV three-phase transmission and established the standards for the complete system of generation, transmission and motors used in USA today.
[src:low-pass-filter/alternating-current] The original Niagara Falls Adams Power Plant with three two-phase generators was put into operation in August 1895, but was connected to the remote transmission system only in 1896.
[src:low-pass-filter/alternating-current] The Jaruga Hydroelectric Power Plant in Croatia was set in operation two days later, on 28 August 1895.
[src:low-pass-filter/alternating-current] Its generator (42 Hz, 240 kW) was made and installed by the Hungarian company Ganz, while the transmission line from the power plant to the City of Šibenik was 11.5 kilometers (7.1 mi) long, and the municipal distribution grid 3000 V/110 V included six transforming stations.
[src:low-pass-filter/alternating-current] Alternating current circuit theory developed rapidly in the latter part of the 19th and early 20th century.
[src:low-pass-filter/alternating-current] Notable contributors to the theoretical basis of alternating current calculations include Charles Steinmetz, Oliver Heaviside, and many others.
[src:low-pass-filter/alternating-current] Calculations in unbalanced three-phase systems were simplified by the symmetrical components methods discussed by Charles LeGeyt Fortescue in 1918.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] In electronics, an **analog-to-digital converter** (**ADC**, **A/D**, or **A-to-D**) is a system that converts an analog signal, such as from fingers touching a touchscreen, sound entering a microphone, or light entering a digital camera, into a digital signal.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] An ADC may also provide an isolated measurement, such as an electronic device that converts an analog input voltage or current to a digital number representing the magnitude of the voltage or current.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] Typically, the digital output is a two's complement binary number that is proportional to the input, but there are other possibilities.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] Due to the complexity and the need for precisely matched components, all but the most specialized ADCs are implemented as integrated circuits (ICs).
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] These typically take the form of metal–oxide–semiconductor (MOS) mixed-signal integrated circuit chips that integrate both analog and digital circuits.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] A digital-to-analog converter (DAC) performs the reverse function; it converts a digital signal into an analog signal.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] An ADC converts a continuous-time and continuous-amplitude analog signal to a discrete-time and discrete-amplitude digital signal.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] The conversion involves quantization of the input, so it necessarily introduces a small amount of quantization error.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] Furthermore, instead of continuously performing the conversion, an ADC does the conversion periodically, sampling the input, and limiting the allowable bandwidth of the input signal.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] The performance of an ADC is primarily characterized by its bandwidth, dynamic range and signal-to-noise and distortion ratio (SNDR).
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] The bandwidth of an ADC is set largely by its sampling rate.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] The SNDR is influenced by many factors, including the resolution, noise floor, linearity and accuracy (how well the quantization levels match the true analog signal).
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] Aliasing and jitter will degrade these specifications.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] The SNDR of an ADC is often summarized in terms of its effective number of bits (ENOB), the number of bits of each measure it returns that are, on average, not noise.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] An ideal ADC has an ENOB equal to its resolution.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] If an ADC operates at a sampling rate greater than twice the bandwidth of the signal, then per the Nyquist–Shannon sampling theorem, near-perfect reconstruction is possible.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] The presence of quantization error limits the SNDR of even an ideal ADC.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] When the SNDR of the ADC exceeds that of the input signal, the effects of quantization error may be neglected, resulting in an essentially perfect digital representation of the bandlimited analog input signal.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] The resolution of the converter indicates the number of different, i.e., discrete, values it can produce over the allowed range of analog input values.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] Thus, a particular resolution determines the magnitude of the quantization error and therefore determines the maximum possible signal-to-noise ratio for an ideal ADC without the use of oversampling.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] The input samples are usually stored electronically in binary form within the ADC, so the resolution is usually expressed in bits.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] Resolution can also be defined electrically, and expressed in volts.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] The change in voltage required to guarantee a change in the output code level is called the least significant bit (LSB) voltage.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] The resolution *Q* of the ADC is equal to the LSB voltage.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] where *M* is the ADC's resolution in bits and *E*FSR is the full-scale voltage range (also called 'span').
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] where *V*RefHi and *V*RefLow are the upper and lower extremes, respectively, of the voltages that can be coded.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] where *M* is the ADC's resolution in bits.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] That is, one voltage interval is assigned in between two consecutive code levels.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] In many cases, the useful resolution of a converter is limited by the signal-to-noise ratio (SNR) and other errors in the overall system expressed as an ENOB.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] Quantization error is introduced by the quantization inherent in an ideal ADC.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] It is a rounding error between the analog input voltage to the ADC and the output digitized value.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] The error is nonlinear and signal-dependent.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] where M is the number of quantization bits.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] For example, for a 16-bit ADC, the quantization error is 96.3 dB below the maximum level.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] Quantization error is distributed from DC to the Nyquist frequency.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] Consequently, if part of the ADC's bandwidth is not used, as is the case with oversampling, some of the quantization error will occur out-of-band, effectively improving the SQNR for the bandwidth in use.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] In an oversampled system, noise shaping can be used to further increase SQNR by forcing more quantization error out of band.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] In ADCs, performance can usually be improved using dither.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] This is a very small amount of random noise (e.g., white noise), which is added to the input before conversion.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] Its effect is to randomize the state of the LSB based on the signal.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] Rather than the signal simply getting cut off altogether at low levels, it extends the effective range of signals that the ADC can convert, at the expense of a slight increase in noise.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] Dither can only increase the resolution of a sampler.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] It cannot improve the linearity, and thus, accuracy does not necessarily improve.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] Quantization distortion in an audio signal of very low level with respect to the bit depth of the ADC is correlated with the signal and sounds distorted and unpleasant.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] With dithering, the distortion is transformed into noise.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] The undistorted signal may be recovered accurately by averaging over time.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] Dithering is also used in integrating systems such as electricity meters.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] Since the values are added together, the dithering produces results that are more exact than the LSB of the analog-to-digital converter.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] Dither is often applied when quantizing photographic images to a fewer number of bits per pixel—the image becomes noisier but to the eye looks far more realistic than the quantized image, which otherwise becomes banded.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] This analogous process may help to visualize the effect of dither on an analog audio signal that is converted to digital.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] Quantization error and (assuming the ADC is intended to be linear) non-linearity are intrinsic to any analog-to-digital conversion.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] These errors are measured in a unit called the least significant bit (LSB).
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] In the above example of an 8-bit ADC, an error of one LSB is 1⁄256 of the full signal range, or about 0.4%.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] All ADCs suffer from nonlinearity errors caused by their physical imperfections, causing their output to deviate from a linear function (or some other function, in the case of a deliberately nonlinear ADC) of their input.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] These errors can sometimes be mitigated by calibration, or prevented by testing.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] Important parameters for linearity are integral nonlinearity and differential nonlinearity.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] These nonlinearities introduce distortion that can reduce the signal-to-noise ratio performance of the ADC and thus reduce its effective resolution.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] When digitizing a sine wave $x(t)=A\sin {(2\pi f_{0}t)}$ , the use of a non-ideal sampling clock will result in some uncertainty in when samples are recorded.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] Provided that the actual sampling time uncertainty due to clock jitter is $\Delta t$ , the error caused by this phenomenon can be estimated as $E_{ap}\leq |x'(t)\Delta t|\leq 2A\pi f_{0}\Delta t$ .
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] This will result in additional recorded noise that will reduce the effective number of bits (ENOB) below that predicted by quantization error alone.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] The error is zero for DC, small at low frequencies, but significant with signals of high amplitude and high frequency.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] The effect of jitter on performance can be compared to quantization error: $\Delta t<{\frac {1}{2^{q}\pi f_{0}}}$ , where q is the number of ADC bits.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] The resolution of ADCs with a digitization bandwidth between 1 MHz and 1 GHz is limited by jitter.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] For lower bandwidth conversions such as when sampling audio signals at 44.1 kHz, clock jitter has a less significant impact on performance.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] An analog signal is continuous in time and it is necessary to convert this to a flow of digital values.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] It is therefore required to define the rate at which new digital values are sampled from the analog signal.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] The rate of new values is called the *sampling rate* or *sampling frequency* of the converter.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] A continuously varying bandlimited signal can be sampled and then the original signal can be reproduced from the discrete-time values by a reconstruction filter.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] The Nyquist–Shannon sampling theorem implies that a faithful reproduction of the original signal is only possible if the sampling rate is higher than twice the highest frequency of the signal.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] Since a practical ADC cannot make an instantaneous conversion, the input value must necessarily be held constant during the time that the converter performs a conversion (called the *conversion time*).
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] An input circuit called a sample and hold performs this task—in most cases by using a capacitor to store the analog voltage at the input, and using an electronic switch or gate to disconnect the capacitor from the input.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] Many ADC integrated circuits include the sample and hold subsystem internally.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] An ADC works by sampling the value of the input at discrete intervals in time.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] Provided that the input is sampled above the Nyquist rate, defined as twice the highest frequency of interest, then all frequencies in the signal can be reconstructed.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] If frequencies above half the Nyquist rate are sampled, they are incorrectly detected as lower frequencies, a process referred to as aliasing.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] Aliasing occurs because instantaneously sampling a function at two or fewer times per cycle results in missed cycles, and therefore, the appearance of an incorrectly lower frequency.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] For example, a 2 kHz sine wave being sampled at 1.5 kHz would be reconstructed as a 500 Hz sine wave.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] To avoid aliasing, the input to an ADC must be low-pass filtered to remove frequencies above half the sampling rate.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] This filter is called an *anti-aliasing filter*, and is essential for a practical ADC system that is applied to analog signals with higher frequency content.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] In applications where protection against aliasing is essential, oversampling may be used to greatly reduce or even eliminate it.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] Although aliasing in most systems is unwanted, it can be exploited to provide simultaneous down-mixing of a band-limited high-frequency signal (see undersampling and frequency mixer).
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] The alias is effectively the lower heterodyne of the signal frequency and sampling frequency.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] For economy, signals are often sampled at the minimum rate required, with the result that the quantization error introduced is white noise spread over the whole passband of the converter.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] Oversampling is typically used in audio frequency ADCs where the required sampling rate (typically 44.1 or 48 kHz) is very low compared to the clock speed of typical transistor circuits (>1 MHz).
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] In this case, the performance of the ADC can be greatly increased at little or no cost.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] Furthermore, as any aliased signals are also typically out of band, aliasing can often be eliminated using very low-cost filters.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] The sliding scale method was introduced in 1963 by Cottini, Gatti, and Svelto as a way to reduce differential nonlinearity in analog-to-digital converters used in radiation detection systems.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] In those applications, the digital output codes of an ADC are accumulated into histograms representing measured particle energies.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] If some output codes correspond to slightly wider or narrower input voltage ranges than others, the resulting *bins* in the histogram are uneven.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] This produces visible structure in what should otherwise be smooth spectra.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] The method works by adding a known random analog offset to the input before conversion and subtracting the corresponding digital value afterward.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] Although the final numerical result is unchanged, each conversion effectively occurs at a different position along the ADC transfer characteristic.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] When many samples are accumulated, the output codes represent an average over several adjacent code widths, reducing the impact of differential nonlinearity.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] There are several common ways of implementing an electronic ADC.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] Resistor-capacitor (RC) circuits have a known voltage charging and discharging curve that can be used to solve for an unknown analog value.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] The Wilkinson ADC is a type of linear ramp converter, originally described by Denys Wilkinson in 1950.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] In this architecture, the input pulse is compared with a linearly voltage ramp generated by charging a capacitor with a constant current source.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] A comparator produces a gate signal that remains active until the ramp reaches the amplitude of the input pulse.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] The duration of this gate interval is therefore proportional to the input amplitude.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] During this interval, pulses from a constant-frequency clock are counted by a register, and the final count represents the digital output.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] Because the ramp can be generated with high precision, the output codes are contiguous and nearly uniform in width, giving the converter good differential linearity.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] The conversion time is proportional to the input amplitude and inversely proportional to the clock frequency, so larger signals require longer conversion times.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] Wilkinson converters were widely used in multichannel analyzers for nuclear spectroscopy through the 1960s and 1970s due to their linearity and suitability for histogram-based measurements.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] and solving for the unknown resistance or capacitance using those starting and ending datapoints.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] This is similar but contrasts with the Wilkinson ADC, which measures an unknown voltage with a known resistance and capacitance, by instead measuring an unknown resistance or capacitance with a known voltage.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] For example, the positive (and/or negative) pulse width from a 555 Timer IC in monostable or astable mode represents the time it takes to charge (and/or discharge) its capacitor from 1⁄3 *V*supply to 2⁄3 *V*supply.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] By sending this pulse into a microcontroller with an accurate clock, the duration of the pulse can be measured and converted using the capacitor charging equation to produce the value of the unknown resistance or capacitance.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] Larger resistances and capacitances will take a longer time to measure than smaller ones.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] And the accuracy is limited by the accuracy of the microcontroller clock and the amount of time available to measure the value, which potentially might even change during measurement or be affected by external parasitics.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] A flash ADC, also known as a parallel search ADC, employs a bank of voltage comparators sampling the input signal in parallel, each with a different voltage threshold.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] The circuit consists of a resistive divider network, a set of voltage comparators and a priority encoder.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] Each node of the resistive divider provides a voltage threshold for one comparator.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] The comparator outputs are applied to a priority encoder, which generates a binary number proportional to the input voltage.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] Flash ADCs have a large die size and high power dissipation.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] They are used in a variety of applications, including video, wideband communications, and for digitizing other fast signals.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] The circuit has the advantage of high speed as the conversion takes place simultaneously rather than sequentially.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] Typical conversion time is 100 ns or less.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] Conversion time is limited only by the speed of the comparator and of the priority encoder.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] This type of ADC has the disadvantage that for each additional output bit, the number of comparators required almost doubles, and the priority encoder becomes more complex.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] A successive-approximation ADC uses a comparator and a binary search to successively narrow a range that contains the input voltage.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] At each successive step, the converter compares the input voltage to the output of an internal digital-to-analog converter (DAC), which initially represents the midpoint of the allowed input voltage range.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] At each step in this process, the approximation is stored in a successive approximation register (SAR) and the output of the digital-to-analog converter is updated for a comparison over a narrower range.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] A ramp-compare ADC produces a saw-tooth signal that ramps up or down, then quickly returns to zero.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] When the ramp starts, a timer starts counting.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] When the ramp voltage matches the input, a comparator fires, and the timer's value is recorded.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] Timed ramp converters can be implemented economically, however, the ramp time may be sensitive to temperature because the circuit generating the ramp is often a simple analog integrator.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] A more accurate converter uses a clocked counter driving a DAC.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] A special advantage of the ramp-compare system is that converting a second signal just requires another comparator and another register to store the timer value.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] To reduce sensitivity to input changes during conversion, a sample and hold can charge a capacitor with the instantaneous input voltage and the converter can time the time required to discharge with a constant current.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] An **integrating ADC** (also **dual-slope** or **multi-slope** ADC) applies the unknown input voltage to the input of an integrator and allows the voltage to ramp for a fixed time period (the run-up period).
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] Then a known reference voltage of opposite polarity is applied to the integrator and is allowed to ramp until the integrator output returns to zero (the run-down period).
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] The input voltage is computed as a function of the reference voltage, the constant run-up time period, and the measured run-down time period.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] The run-down time measurement is usually made in units of the converter's clock, so longer integration times allow for higher resolutions.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] Likewise, the speed of the converter can be improved by sacrificing resolution.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] Converters of this type (or variations on the concept) are used in most digital voltmeters for their linearity and flexibility.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] This frequency is then measured by a counter and converted to an output code proportional to the analog input.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] The main advantage of these converters is that it is possible to transmit frequency even in a noisy environment or in isolated form.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] However, the limitation of this circuit is that the output of the voltage-to-frequency converter depends upon an RC product whose value cannot be accurately maintained over temperature and time.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] The analog part of the circuit consists of a high input impedance buffer, precision integrator and a voltage comparator.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] The converter first integrates the analog input signal for a fixed duration and then it integrates an internal reference voltage of opposite polarity until the integrator output is zero.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] The main disadvantage of this circuit is the long duration time.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] A *delta-encoded* or *counter-ramp* ADC has an up-down counter that feeds a DAC.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] The input signal and the DAC both go to a comparator.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] The circuit uses negative feedback from the comparator to adjust the counter until the DAC's output matches the input signal and number is read from the counter.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] Delta converters have very wide ranges and high resolution, but the conversion time is dependent on the input signal behavior, though it will always have a guaranteed worst-case.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] Delta converters are often very good choices to read real-world signals as most signals from physical systems do not change abruptly.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] Some converters combine the delta and successive approximation approaches; this works especially well when high-frequency components of the input signal are known to be small in magnitude.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] A *pipelined ADC* (also called *subranging quantizer*) uses two or more conversion steps.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] In a second step, the difference to the input signal is determined with a DAC.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] This difference is then converted more precisely, and the results are combined in the last step.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] This can be considered a refinement of the successive-approximation ADC wherein the feedback reference signal consists of the interim conversion of a whole range of bits (for example, four bits) rather than just the next-most-significant bit.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] By combining the merits of the successive approximation and flash ADCs this type is fast, has a high resolution, and can be implemented efficiently.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] A **delta-sigma ADC** (also known as a **sigma-delta ADC**) is based on a negative feedback loop with an analog filter and low resolution (often 1 bit) but high sampling rate ADC and DAC.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] The feedback loop continuously corrects accumulated quantization errors and performs noise shaping: quantization noise is reduced in the low frequencies of interest, but is increased in higher frequencies.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] Those higher frequencies may then be removed by a downsampling digital filter, which also converts the data stream from that high sampling rate with low bit depth to a lower rate with higher bit depth.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] A time-interleaved ADC uses M parallel ADCs where each ADC samples data every M:th cycle of the effective sample clock.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] The result is that the sample rate is increased M times compared to what each individual ADC can manage.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] In practice, the individual differences between the M ADCs degrade the overall performance reducing the spurious-free dynamic range (SFDR).
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] However, techniques exist to correct for these time-interleaving mismatch errors.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] Longer integration times allow for higher resolutions.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] The two parts of the ADC may be widely separated, with the frequency signal passed through an opto-isolator or transmitted wirelessly.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] Some such ADCs use sine wave or square wave frequency modulation; others use pulse-frequency modulation.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] Such ADCs were once the most popular way to show a digital display of the status of a remote analog sensor.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] A time-stretch analog-to-digital converter (TS-ADC) digitizes a very wide bandwidth analog signal, that cannot be digitized by a conventional electronic ADC, by time-stretching the signal prior to digitization.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] It commonly uses a photonic preprocessor to time-stretch the signal, which effectively slows the signal down in time and compresses its bandwidth.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] As a result, an electronic ADC, that would have been too slow to capture the original signal, can now capture this slowed-down signal.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] For continuous capture of the signal, the front end also divides the signal into multiple segments in addition to time-stretching.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] Each segment is individually digitized by a separate electronic ADC.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] Finally, a digital signal processor rearranges the samples and removes any distortions added by the preprocessor to yield the binary data that is the digital representation of the original analog signal.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] In many cases, the most expensive part of an integrated circuit is the pins, because they make the package larger, and each pin has to be connected to the integrated circuit's silicon.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] To save pins, it is common for ADCs to send their data one bit at a time over a serial interface to the computer, with each bit coming out when a clock signal changes state.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] This saves quite a few pins on the ADC package, and in many cases, does not make the overall design any more complex.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] Commercial ADCs often have several inputs that feed the same converter, usually through an analog multiplexer.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] Different models of ADC may include sample and hold circuits, instrumentation amplifiers or differential inputs, where the quantity measured is the difference between two inputs.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] Soundstream was probably the first digital audio recording system of commercial importance.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] Analog-to-digital converters are integral to modern music reproduction technology and digital audio workstation-based sound recording.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] Music may be produced on computers using an analog recording and therefore analog-to-digital converters are needed to create the pulse-code modulation (PCM) data streams that go onto compact discs and digital music files.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] The current crop of analog-to-digital converters utilized in music can sample at rates up to 192 kilohertz.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] Many recording studios record in 24-bit 96 kHz pulse-code modulation (PCM) format and then downsample and dither the signal for Compact Disc Digital Audio production (44.1 kHz) or to 48 kHz for radio and television broadcast applications.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] ADCs are required in digital signal processing systems that process, store, or transport virtually any analog signal in digital form.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] TV tuner cards, for example, use fast video analog-to-digital converters.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] Slow on-chip 8-, 10-, 12-, or 16-bit analog-to-digital converters are common in microcontrollers.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] Digital storage oscilloscopes need very fast analog-to-digital converters, also crucial for software-defined radio and their new applications.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] Digital imaging systems commonly use analog-to-digital converters for digitizing pixels.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] Some radar systems use analog-to-digital converters to convert signal strength to digital values for subsequent signal processing.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] Many other in situ and remote sensing systems commonly use analogous technology.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] Many sensors in scientific instruments produce an analog signal; temperature, pressure, pH, light intensity etc.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] All these signals can be amplified and fed to an ADC to produce a digital representation.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] Flat-panel displays are inherently digital and need an ADC to process an analog signal such as composite or VGA.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] Testing an analog-to-digital converter requires an analog input source and hardware to send control signals and capture digital data output.
[src:low-pass-filter/analog-to-digital-conversion] Some ADCs also require an accurate source of reference signal.
[src:low-pass-filter/low-pass-filter] A **low-pass filter** is a filter that passes signals with a frequency lower than a selected cutoff frequency and attenuates signals with frequencies higher than the cutoff frequency.
[src:low-pass-filter/low-pass-filter] The exact frequency response of the filter depends on the filter design.
[src:low-pass-filter/low-pass-filter] The filter is sometimes called a **high-cut filter**, or **treble-cut filter** in audio applications.
[src:low-pass-filter/low-pass-filter] A low-pass filter is the complement of a high-pass filter.
[src:low-pass-filter/low-pass-filter] In optics, **high-pass** and **low-pass** may have different meanings, depending on whether referring to the frequency or wavelength of light, since these variables are inversely related.
[src:low-pass-filter/low-pass-filter] High-pass frequency filters would act as low-pass wavelength filters, and vice versa.
[src:low-pass-filter/low-pass-filter] For this reason, it is a good practice to refer to wavelength filters as *short-pass* and *long-pass* to avoid confusion, which would correspond to *high-pass* and *low-pass* frequencies.
[src:low-pass-filter/low-pass-filter] Low-pass filters exist in many different forms, including electronic circuits such as a *hiss filter* used in audio, anti-aliasing filters for conditioning signals before analog-to-digital conversion, digital filters for smoothing sets of data, acoustic barriers, blurring of images, and so on.
[src:low-pass-filter/low-pass-filter] The moving average operation used in fields such as finance is a particular kind of low-pass filter and can be analyzed with the same signal processing techniques as are used for other low-pass filters.
[src:low-pass-filter/low-pass-filter] Low-pass filters provide a smoother form of a signal, removing the short-term fluctuations and leaving the longer-term trend.
[src:low-pass-filter/low-pass-filter] Filter designers will often use the low-pass form as a prototype filter.
[src:low-pass-filter/low-pass-filter] That is a filter with unity bandwidth and impedance.
[src:low-pass-filter/low-pass-filter] The desired filter is obtained from the prototype by scaling for the desired bandwidth and impedance and transforming into the desired bandform (that is, low-pass, high-pass, band-pass or band-stop).
[src:low-pass-filter/low-pass-filter] Examples of low-pass filters occur in acoustics, optics and electronics.
[src:low-pass-filter/low-pass-filter] A stiff physical barrier tends to reflect higher sound frequencies, acting as an acoustic low-pass filter for transmitting sound.
[src:low-pass-filter/low-pass-filter] When music is playing in another room, the low notes are easily heard, while the high notes are attenuated.
[src:low-pass-filter/low-pass-filter] An optical filter with the same function can correctly be called a low-pass filter, but conventionally is called a *longpass* filter (low frequency is long wavelength), to avoid confusion.
[src:low-pass-filter/low-pass-filter] In an electronic low-pass RC filter for voltage signals, high frequencies in the input signal are attenuated, but the filter has little attenuation below the cutoff frequency determined by its RC time constant.
[src:low-pass-filter/low-pass-filter] For current signals, a similar circuit, using a resistor and capacitor in parallel, works in a similar manner.
[src:low-pass-filter/low-pass-filter] Electronic low-pass filters are used on inputs to subwoofers and other types of loudspeakers, to block high pitches that they cannot efficiently reproduce.
[src:low-pass-filter/low-pass-filter] Radio transmitters use low-pass filters to block harmonic emissions that might interfere with other communications.
[src:low-pass-filter/low-pass-filter] The tone knob on many electric guitars is a low-pass filter used to reduce the amount of treble in the sound.
[src:low-pass-filter/low-pass-filter] An integrator is another time constant low-pass filter.
[src:low-pass-filter/low-pass-filter] Telephone lines fitted with DSL splitters use low-pass filters to separate DSL from POTS signals (and high-pass vice versa), which share the same pair of wires (*transmission channel*).
[src:low-pass-filter/low-pass-filter] Low-pass filters also play a significant role in the sculpting of sound created by analogue and virtual analogue synthesisers.
[src:low-pass-filter/low-pass-filter] A low-pass filter is used as an anti-aliasing filter before sampling and for reconstruction in digital-to-analog conversion.
[src:low-pass-filter/low-pass-filter] An ideal low-pass filter completely eliminates all frequencies above the cutoff frequency while passing those below unchanged; its frequency response is a rectangular function and is a brick-wall filter.
[src:low-pass-filter/low-pass-filter] The transition region present in practical filters does not exist in an ideal filter.
[src:low-pass-filter/low-pass-filter] An ideal low-pass filter can be realized mathematically (theoretically) by multiplying a signal by the rectangular function in the frequency domain or, equivalently, convolution with its impulse response, a sinc function, in the time domain.
[src:low-pass-filter/low-pass-filter] However, the ideal filter is impossible to realize without also having signals of infinite extent in time, and so generally needs to be approximated for real ongoing signals, because the sinc function's support region extends to all past and future times.
[src:low-pass-filter/low-pass-filter] The filter would therefore need to have infinite delay, or knowledge of the infinite future and past, to perform the convolution.
[src:low-pass-filter/low-pass-filter] It is effectively realizable for pre-recorded digital signals by assuming extensions of zero into the past and future, or, more typically, by making the signal repetitive and using Fourier analysis.
[src:low-pass-filter/low-pass-filter] This delay is manifested as phase shift.
[src:low-pass-filter/low-pass-filter] Greater accuracy in approximation requires a longer delay.
[src:low-pass-filter/low-pass-filter] Truncating an ideal low-pass filter result in ringing artifacts via the Gibbs phenomenon, which can be reduced or worsened by the choice of windowing function.
[src:low-pass-filter/low-pass-filter] Design and choice of real filters involves understanding and minimizing these artifacts.
[src:low-pass-filter/low-pass-filter] For example, simple truncation of the sinc function will create severe ringing artifacts, which can be reduced using window functions that drop off more smoothly at the edges.
[src:low-pass-filter/low-pass-filter] The time response of a low-pass filter is found by solving the response to the simple low-pass RC filter.
[src:low-pass-filter/low-pass-filter] where $\omega _{0}={1 \over RC}$ is the cutoff frequency of the filter.
[src:low-pass-filter/low-pass-filter] The most common way to characterize the frequency response of a circuit is to find its Laplace transform transfer function, $H(s)={V_{\rm {out}}(s) \over V_{\rm {in}}(s)}$ .
[src:low-pass-filter/low-pass-filter] A discrete difference equation is easily obtained by sampling the step input response above at regular intervals of $nT$ where $n=0,1,...$ and T is the time between samples.
[src:low-pass-filter/low-pass-filter] Comparing the reconstructed output signal from the difference equation, $V_{n}=\beta V_{n-1}+(1-\beta )v_{n}$ , to the step input response, $v_{\text{out}}(t)=V_{i}(1-e^{-\omega _{0}t})$ , we find that there is an exact reconstruction (0% error).
[src:low-pass-filter/low-pass-filter] This is the reconstructed output for a time-invariant input.
[src:low-pass-filter/low-pass-filter] However, if the input is *time variant*, such as $v_{\text{in}}(t)=V_{i}\sin(\omega t)$ , this model approximates the input signal as a series of step functions with duration T producing an error in the reconstructed output signal.
[src:low-pass-filter/low-pass-filter] The error produced from *time variant* inputs is difficult to quantify but decreases as $T\rightarrow 0$ .
[src:low-pass-filter/low-pass-filter] Many digital filters are designed to give low-pass characteristics.
[src:low-pass-filter/low-pass-filter] Both infinite impulse response and finite impulse response low pass filters, as well as filters using Fourier transforms, are widely used.
[src:low-pass-filter/low-pass-filter] The effect of an infinite impulse response low-pass filter can be simulated on a computer by analyzing an RC filter's behavior in the time domain, and then discretizing the model.
[src:low-pass-filter/low-pass-filter] where $Q_{c}(t)$ is the charge stored in the capacitor at time t.
[src:low-pass-filter/low-pass-filter] For simplicity, assume that samples of the input and output are taken at evenly spaced points in time separated by $\Delta _{T}$ time.
[src:low-pass-filter/low-pass-filter] By definition, the *smoothing factor* is within the range $0\;\leq \;\alpha \;\leq \;1$ .
[src:low-pass-filter/low-pass-filter] If α=0.5, then the *RC* time constant equals the sampling period.
[src:low-pass-filter/low-pass-filter] If $\alpha \;\ll \;0.5$ , then *RC* is significantly larger than the sampling interval, and $\Delta _{T}\;\approx \;\alpha RC$ .
[src:low-pass-filter/low-pass-filter] The filter recurrence relation provides a way to determine the output samples in terms of the input samples and the preceding output.
[src:low-pass-filter/low-pass-filter] That is, the change from one filter output to the next is proportional to the difference between the previous output and the next input.
[src:low-pass-filter/low-pass-filter] This exponential smoothing property matches the exponential decay seen in the continuous-time system.
[src:low-pass-filter/low-pass-filter] As expected, as the time constant *RC* increases, the discrete-time smoothing parameter $\alpha$ decreases, and the output samples $(y_{1},\,y_{2},\,\ldots ,\,y_{n})$ respond more slowly to a change in the input samples $(x_{1},\,x_{2},\,\ldots ,\,x_{n})$ ; the system has more *inertia*.
[src:low-pass-filter/low-pass-filter] This filter is an infinite-impulse-response (IIR) single-pole low-pass filter.
[src:low-pass-filter/low-pass-filter] Finite-impulse-response filters can be built that approximate the sinc function time-domain response of an ideal sharp-cutoff low-pass filter.
[src:low-pass-filter/low-pass-filter] For minimum distortion, the finite impulse response filter has an unbounded number of coefficients operating on an unbounded signal.
[src:low-pass-filter/low-pass-filter] In practice, the time-domain response must be time truncated and is often of a simplified shape; in the simplest case, a running average can be used, giving a square time response.
[src:low-pass-filter/low-pass-filter] For non-realtime filtering, to achieve a low pass filter, the entire signal is usually taken as a looped signal, the Fourier transform is taken, filtered in the frequency domain, followed by an inverse Fourier transform.
[src:low-pass-filter/low-pass-filter] Only O(n log(n)) operations are required compared to O(n2) for the time domain filtering algorithm.
[src:low-pass-filter/low-pass-filter] This can also sometimes be done in real time, where the signal is delayed long enough to perform the Fourier transformation on shorter, overlapping blocks.
[src:low-pass-filter/low-pass-filter] There are many different types of filter circuits, with different responses to changing frequency.
[src:low-pass-filter/low-pass-filter] The frequency response of a filter is generally represented using a Bode plot, and the filter is characterized by its cutoff frequency and rate of frequency rolloff.
[src:low-pass-filter/low-pass-filter] In all cases, at the *cutoff frequency,* the filter attenuates the input power by half or 3 dB.
[src:low-pass-filter/low-pass-filter] So the **order** of the filter determines the amount of additional attenuation for frequencies higher than the cutoff frequency.
[src:low-pass-filter/low-pass-filter] On any Butterworth filter, if one extends the horizontal line to the right and the diagonal line to the upper-left (the asymptotes of the function), they intersect at exactly the *cutoff frequency*, 3 dB below the horizontal line.
[src:low-pass-filter/low-pass-filter] The various types of filters (Butterworth filter, Chebyshev filter, Bessel filter, etc.) all have different-looking *knee curves*.
[src:low-pass-filter/low-pass-filter] Many second-order filters have "peaking" or resonance that puts their frequency response *above* the horizontal line at this peak.
[src:low-pass-filter/low-pass-filter] The meanings of 'low' and 'high'—that is, the cutoff frequency—depend on the characteristics of the filter.
[src:low-pass-filter/low-pass-filter] The term "low-pass filter" merely refers to the shape of the filter's response; a high-pass filter could be built that cuts off at a lower frequency than any low-pass filter—it is their responses that set them apart.
[src:low-pass-filter/low-pass-filter] Electronic circuits can be devised for any desired frequency range, right up through microwave frequencies (above 1 GHz) and higher.
[src:low-pass-filter/low-pass-filter] Continuous-time filters can also be described in terms of the Laplace transform of their impulse response, in a way that makes it easy to analyze all characteristics of the filter by considering the pattern of poles and zeros of the Laplace transform in the complex plane.
[src:low-pass-filter/low-pass-filter] where *H* is the transfer function, *s* is the Laplace transform variable (complex angular frequency), *τ* is the filter time constant, $\alpha$ is the cutoff frequency, and *K* is the gain of the filter in the passband.
[src:low-pass-filter/low-pass-filter] One simple low-pass filter circuit consists of a resistor in series with a load, and a capacitor in parallel with the load.
[src:low-pass-filter/low-pass-filter] The capacitor exhibits reactance, and blocks low-frequency signals, forcing them through the load instead.
[src:low-pass-filter/low-pass-filter] At higher frequencies, the reactance drops, and the capacitor effectively functions as a short circuit.
[src:low-pass-filter/low-pass-filter] The combination of resistance and capacitance gives the time constant of the filter $\tau \;=\;RC$ (represented by the Greek letter tau).
[src:low-pass-filter/low-pass-filter] The capacitor is not an "on/off" object (like the block or pass fluidic explanation above).
[src:low-pass-filter/low-pass-filter] The capacitor variably acts between these two extremes.
[src:low-pass-filter/low-pass-filter] It is the Bode plot and frequency response that show this variability.
[src:low-pass-filter/low-pass-filter] A resistor–inductor circuit or RL filter is an electric circuit composed of resistors and inductors driven by a voltage or current source.
[src:low-pass-filter/low-pass-filter] A first-order RL circuit is composed of one resistor and one inductor and is the simplest type of RL circuit.
[src:low-pass-filter/low-pass-filter] A first-order RL circuit is one of the simplest analogue infinite impulse response electronic filters.
[src:low-pass-filter/low-pass-filter] It consists of a resistor and an inductor, either in series driven by a voltage source or in parallel driven by a current source.
[src:low-pass-filter/low-pass-filter] An RLC circuit (the letters R, L, and C can be in a different sequence) is an electrical circuit consisting of a resistor, an inductor, and a capacitor, connected in series or in parallel.
[src:low-pass-filter/low-pass-filter] The RLC part of the name is due to those letters being the usual electrical symbols for resistance, inductance, and capacitance, respectively.
[src:low-pass-filter/low-pass-filter] The circuit forms a harmonic oscillator for current and will resonate in a similar way as an LC circuit will.
[src:low-pass-filter/low-pass-filter] The main difference that the presence of the resistor makes is that any oscillation induced in the circuit will die away over time if it is not kept going by a source.
[src:low-pass-filter/low-pass-filter] This effect of the resistor is called damping.
[src:low-pass-filter/low-pass-filter] The presence of the resistance also reduces the peak resonant frequency somewhat.
[src:low-pass-filter/low-pass-filter] Some resistance is unavoidable in real circuits, even if a resistor is not specifically included as a component.
[src:low-pass-filter/low-pass-filter] An ideal, pure LC circuit is an abstraction for the purpose of theory.
[src:low-pass-filter/low-pass-filter] There are many applications for this circuit.
[src:low-pass-filter/low-pass-filter] They are used in many different types of oscillator circuits.
[src:low-pass-filter/low-pass-filter] Another important application is for tuning, such as in radio receivers or television sets, where they are used to select a narrow range of frequencies from the ambient radio waves.
[src:low-pass-filter/low-pass-filter] In this role, the circuit is often called a tuned circuit.
[src:low-pass-filter/low-pass-filter] An RLC circuit can be used as a band-pass filter, band-stop filter, low-pass filter, or high-pass filter.
[src:low-pass-filter/low-pass-filter] The RLC filter is described as a *second-order* circuit, meaning that any voltage or current in the circuit can be described by a second-order differential equation in circuit analysis.
[src:low-pass-filter/low-pass-filter] The transfer function $H_{LP}(f)$ of a second-order low-pass filter can be expressed as a function of frequency f as shown in Equation 1, the Second-Order Low-Pass Filter Standard Form.
[src:low-pass-filter/low-pass-filter] In this equation, f is the frequency variable, $f_{c}$ is the cutoff frequency, $f_{FSF}$ is the frequency scaling factor, and Q is the quality factor.
[src:low-pass-filter/low-pass-filter] Equation 1 describes three regions of operation: below cutoff, in the area of cutoff, and above cutoff.
[src:low-pass-filter/low-pass-filter] With attenuation at frequencies above $f_{c}$ increasing by a power of two, the last formula describes a second-order low-pass filter.
[src:low-pass-filter/low-pass-filter] The frequency scaling factor $f_{FSF}$ is used to scale the cutoff frequency of the filter so that it follows the definitions given before.
[src:low-pass-filter/low-pass-filter] Higher-order passive filters can also be constructed (see diagram for a third-order example).
[src:low-pass-filter/low-pass-filter] An *active* low-pass filter adds an active device to create an active filter that allows for gain in the passband.
[src:low-pass-filter/low-pass-filter] The gain in the passband is −*R*2/*R*1, and the stopband drops off at −6 dB per octave (that is −20 dB per decade) as it is a first-order filter.
